In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims December 1, 2010, as World AIDS Day. He reflects on the thirtieth year of the HIV/AIDS pandemic and expresses support for the 33 million people worldwide living with HIV/AIDS. The President emphasizes the need to continue efforts in preventing the spread of the disease, combating stigma and discrimination, and finding a cure. He highlights the domestic HIV epidemic and the release of the National HIV/AIDS Strategy for the United States, which focuses on comprehensive, evidence-based approaches to prevention, care, and reducing health disparities. President Obama also mentions the Affordable Care Act, which provides greater access to health insurance coverage and care for individuals living with HIV/AIDS. He discusses the government's role in reducing stigma, such as eliminating the entry ban for individuals living with HIV/AIDS entering the United States. The President acknowledges the shared response required to tackle the disease, highlighting the President's Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR) and the Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria as programs supporting prevention and treatment efforts globally. He emphasizes the ongoing impact of HIV/AIDS, with over one million Americans living with the disease and over 56,000 new infections each year. President Obama calls for remembrance of those lost to AIDS and support for those living with the disease.